Spectral Density

The idea that a time series is composed of periodic components, appearing in proportion to their underlying variances, is fundamental in the spectral representation. The result, called the Spectral Representation Theorem, serves as a connection between the spectral density and the autocovariance functions.

Spectral Representation Theorem

If the autocovariance function, \(\gamma(h)\), of a stationary process satisfies \[\sum_{j=1}^\infty|\gamma(h)|<\infty, \qquad\text{i.e., absolutely summable}\] then it has the representation \[\gamma(h)=\int_{-1/2}^{1/2}e^{2\pi i \omega h}f(\omega)d\omega, \qquad h=0,\pm 1, \pm 2, \dots.\] On the other hand the spectral density has the representation \[f(\omega)=\sum_{h=-\infty}^{\infty}\gamma(h)e^{-2\pi i \omega h}, \qquad -1/2\leq \omega \leq 1/2.\]

White noise:

To find the power spectral density of white noise \(\varepsilon_t\sim(0,\sigma^2_\varepsilon)\), one needs to find the autocovariance function first. Recall the autocovariance function of white noise is \(\gamma(h)=\sigma^2_\varepsilon\) if \(h=0\) and \(\gamma(h)=0\) if \(h\neq 0\). Then the power spectrum (spectral density) is: \[f_\varepsilon(\omega) = \sum_{h=-\infty}^{\infty}\gamma(h)e^{-2\pi i \omega h} = \gamma(0)e^{-2\pi i \omega(0)}=\gamma(0)=\sigma^2_\varepsilon.\]

MA(1) process

Consider the MA(1) process: \[X_t = \varepsilon_t + \theta \varepsilon_{t-1},\] where \(\theta\) is a parameter.

Part a

In order to derive a formula for the spectral density of \(X_t\), expressed in terms of \(\theta\) and \(\omega\), we first need to recall the autocovariance function of MA(1) process \(X_t\), i.e.,

\[ \gamma_X(h)=\begin{cases} (1+\theta^2)\sigma^2 & h= 0 \\ \theta\sigma^2 & |h|=1 \\ 0 & |h|>1 \end{cases}, \qquad \text{VERIFY THIS!} \]

Then the spectral density of \(X_t\) is given by:

\[\begin{align*} f_X(\omega) &= \sum_{h=-\infty}^{\infty}\gamma_x(h)e^{-2\pi i \omega h} \\ & = \gamma_x(-1)e^{2\pi i\omega}+\gamma_x(0)+\gamma_x(1)e^{-2\pi i \omega} \\ & = \theta\sigma^2\underbrace{[e^{2\pi i\omega}+e^{-2\pi i\omega}]}_{2\cos(2\pi \omega)}+(1+\theta^2)\sigma^2\\ & = \sigma^2[1+2\theta\cos(2\pi \omega)+\theta^2] \end{align*}\]

Note that the above identity comes from the property: \[e^{i\alpha} = \cos(\alpha)+i\sin(\alpha).\] In above equation we have

\[\begin{align*} [e^{2\pi i \omega}+e^{-2\pi i \omega}] &= \cos(2\pi \omega) + i\sin(2\pi \omega)+ \cos(-2\pi \omega) + i\sin(-2\pi \omega) \\ & = \cos(2\pi \omega) + i\sin(2\pi \omega)+ \cos(2\pi \omega) - i\sin(2\pi \omega) \\ & = 2\cos(2\pi \omega) \end{align*}\]

Part b

Assuming \(\theta=0.5\)

library(astsa)
arma.spec(ma=0.5)

and also assuming \(\theta=-0.5\)

library(astsa)
arma.spec(ma=-0.5)

Part c

when \(\theta>0\) (the first plot), it seems that the low frequencies have a larger spectrum, whereas when \(\theta<0\) (second plot), it is reversed and the high frequencies have a larger spectrum.

The Spectral Density of ARMA (Property 4.2)

If \(X_t\) has an ARMA(\(p,q\)), with \(\phi(B)X_t = \theta(B)\varepsilon_t\), its spectral density is given by \[f_X(\omega)=\sigma^2_\varepsilon|\psi(e^{-2\pi i \omega})|^2 = \frac{|\theta(e^{-2\pi i \omega})|^2}{|\phi(e^{-2\pi i \omega})|^2}\sigma^2_\varepsilon.\] where \(\phi(z)=1-\sum_{j=1}^p\phi_kz^j\), and \(\theta(z)=1+\sum_{j=1}^q\theta_kz^j\), and \(\psi(z)=\sum_{k=0}^\infty\psi_kz^k\).

AR(1) process

Consider a first-order autoregressive model \[X_t = \phi X_{t-1}+\varepsilon_t\] where \(\phi\), for \(|\phi|<1\), is a parameter and the \(\varepsilon_t\) are independent random variables with mean zero and variance \(\sigma^2_\varepsilon\).

Here we will derive the spectral density function for \(X_t\) by using the above property. Note that the AR polynomial of AR(1) is \(\phi(z)=1-\phi z\), and the MA polynomial is just \(\theta(z)=1\) (since we have only AR process). We have

\[\begin{align*} f_X(\omega) &= \frac{1}{|\phi(e^{-2\pi i \omega})|^2}\sigma^2_\varepsilon \end{align*}\] Note that for any complex number \(z=a+ib\), we have the identity \[|z|^2=(a+ib)(a-ib)=a^2+b^2.\] Hence we have \[\begin{align*} |\phi(e^{-2\pi i \omega})|^2 &= |1-\phi e^{-2\pi i \omega}|^2 \\ &= (1-\phi e^{-2\pi i \omega})(1-\phi e^{2\pi i \omega}) \\ &= 1 - \phi\underbrace{(e^{-2\pi i \omega}+e^{2\pi i \omega})}_{2\cos(2\pi \omega)} + \phi^2 \\ &= 1-2\phi\cos(2\pi \omega)+\phi^2, \end{align*}\]

and the spectral density is \[f_X(\omega) = \frac{\sigma^2_\omega}{1-2\phi\cos(2\pi \omega)+\phi^2}.\]

Part a

t = 1:100
x1 = 2*cos(2*pi*t*6/100) + 3*sin(2*pi*t*6/100)
x2 = 4*cos(2*pi*t*10/100) + 5*sin(2*pi*t*10/100)
x3 = 6*cos(2*pi*t*40/100) + 7*sin(2*pi*t*40/100)
x =x1+x2+x3

t = 1:128
x.1 = 2*cos(2*pi*t*6/100) + 3*sin(2*pi*t*6/100)
x.2 = 4*cos(2*pi*t*10/100) + 5*sin(2*pi*t*10/100)
x.3 = 6*cos(2*pi*t*40/100) + 7*sin(2*pi*t*40/100)
x.f =x.1+x.2+x.3

par(mfrow=c(4,2))
plot.ts(x1, ylim=c(-10,10), main=expression(omega==6/100~~~A^2==13~~~n==100))
plot.ts(x.1, ylim=c(-10,10), main=expression(omega==6/100~~~A^2==13~~~n==128))
plot.ts(x2, ylim=c(-10,10), main=expression(omega==10/100~~~A^2==41~~~n==100))
plot.ts(x.2, ylim=c(-10,10), main=expression(omega==10/100~~~A^2==41~~~n==128))
plot.ts(x3, ylim=c(-10,10), main=expression(omega==40/100~~~A^2==85~~~n==100))
plot.ts(x.3, ylim=c(-10,10), main=expression(omega==40/100~~~A^2==85~~~n==128))
plot.ts(x, ylim=c(-10,10), main="sum, n=100")
plot.ts(x.f, ylim=c(-10,10), main="sum, n=128")

Note that the difference is the fundamental frequencies, i.e., \(w_j=j/n\) where \(j\) is the cycles and \(n\) is the sample size. For the first process when \(n=100\), the fundamental frequency is \(6/100\) since there are total of \(6\) cycles, where as when \(n=128\), we have roughly \(j=7.5\) cyles which gives \(7.5/100=0.058\) as a fundamental frequency. This applies to all four peocesses above.

Part b

To plot the periodogram, one can either follow the steps from previous discussion using the fast Fourier transform, or simply use the R function \(spec.pgram()\)

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
spec.pgram(x.1)
spec.pgram(x.2)
spec.pgram(x,3)
spec.pgram(x.f)

Part c

new.d = x + rnorm(100,0,5)
plot.ts(new.d)

spec.pgram(new.d)

The periodogram of the new data has the similar dominant frequencies as the the non-noisy data, and adding the white noise seems not to affect the dominant frequency.

Smoothing

The same function can also compute periodogram values smoothed with the Daniell kernel. The argument spans has to be an odd number, and corresponds to the number of points to average over using the kernel.

For example, if spans=7, then each value of the smoothed periodogram is computed by a weighted average of 7 raw periodogram values.

set.seed(746)
x = arima.sim(n=100, model=list(ar=c(-0.3, 0.5)))

spans = c(3, 5, 9, 13, 17, 25, 31)

par(mfrow = c(3,3))
spec.pgram(x)
for(k in spans){
spec.pgram(x, spans=k, main=paste0('Span ', k))
}
arma.spec(ar=c(-0.3, 0.5), main = 'True Spectral Density')
